ch for the mass of society (inequality in the middle of the income spectrum actually decreased) but between the very top and the bottom. The average investor became richer again. Com-1 World Top Income Database and Luxembourg Income Study 1 pared to his investment decisions in the past, he now based his decisions more on expected returns now played a larger role relative to variances. As a result, normal industry and generally the entrenchedly-secure but slow-evolving demand patterns of Western markets became less interesting than financial games and risky-but-dynamic periphery markets. Furthermore, as the growing inequality also reduced internal de-mand in Western countries, the already expected returns to investments in the West decreased, providing a second reason for a ship in investment out of industry and into periphery countries. Another effect of the change in inequality has been the expan-sion of available loans, enabling a structural break in the previously-stable relation of private debt to real output. Related to the above problems is personal income tax competition. Historically, most tax havens were created in the same period of the income tax reforms (see Palan). Which event drove which is unclear. Defendants of Reagan/Thatcher/Deng/Kohl argue that Western states had to lower top marginal income taxes in order to prevent the off-flow of high incomes. But if that was the intention, it failed, because the income tax reforms were followed by big out-flows. According to the alternative explanation, the income tax reforms raised inequality, which put a larger number of top incomes beyond a certain threshold required for income shifting to be lucrative. In any case, the tax reforms lowered public revenues twice: through the reduced income tax rates themselves and through the subsequent era of " tax base erosion " were high incomes were shifted from large countries into micro-states. Both effects were the opposite of Rumsfeld's " Laffer Curve " at the initia